No party is immune to redistricting abuse. Republicans do it in red states, Democrats do it in blue states. That‚Äôs why both parties must come together to take the politics out of redistricting. Candidates should win on their ideas and merits, not bc their party rigged the system.

Overcoming gerrymandering isnt impossible, just extremely rare. Our district was rigged for the GOP by 10 pts and it didnt flip for 40 yrs. When we won, some called it the biggest upset in SC history. Not bc of the types of campaigns we ran, but bc of how the district was drawn.

Fewer general elections favor incumbents, you know, the folks drawing the lines. And when a district is rigged for one particular party, the winner of the primary is usually the most conservative or liberal. That‚Äôs why we have very few moderate politicians anymore.

They have the authority to cut deals with other legislators to make their districts ‚Äúsafer‚Äù so they are less likely to face a tough general election opponent. This results in very few competitive general elections and more competitive primaries.

Every 10 yrs, partisan politicians use the power of redistricting to draw district lines in a way that protects their own political interests. It‚Äôs time to take that power away and let independent commissions draw them in a more fair and equitable manner. https://t.co/UGy6NLk6OA

Final: There are more indictments coming out of DC and Columbia than good ideas these days. It‚Äôs time to overhaul the system that allows it.
10. Ban fundraising while Congress is in session. Members should be working while in DC. Instead of fundraisers, spend time reading bills.
9. Ban roll-over campaign dollars. Require fed candidates to zero-out their campaign accounts after each cycle. If unopposed, must return $.
8. One person, one pension. Ban politicians from double dipping and receiving multiple pensions at one time for separate political offices.
7. Real-time campaign account monitoring. Candidates use central bank for campaign accts so public can view donations/spending in real time.
6. Close the revolving door. Increase the wait period for former members of Congress to become lobbyists from 1 year to 5 years.
